WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:22.630 --> 00:00:25.690
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: Good afternoon,
everyone, and thank you all

00:00:25.690 --> 00:00:28.500
for coming to the African
Middle-East Division.

00:00:28.500 --> 00:00:30.950
I'm Mary-Jane Deeb,
Chief of the Division,

00:00:30.950 --> 00:00:32.810
and I'm delighted to see you all.

00:00:32.810 --> 00:00:37.290
We have with us -- I want
to recognize Chris Murphy,

00:00:37.290 --> 00:00:40.870
who is the Head of the Near East
Section here for many, many years,

00:00:40.870 --> 00:00:47.810
and a colleague, and also Michael
Albin, who was a comrade in arms

00:00:47.810 --> 00:00:50.120
when we went to Iraq together.

00:00:50.120 --> 00:00:55.060
And he was the Head of the
Anglo-American Acquisitions,

00:00:55.060 --> 00:00:58.930
and also Director of
our office in Cairo.

00:00:58.930 --> 00:01:06.040
I want just to say a few
words about our division.

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:09.230
Our division is made
up of three sections,

00:01:09.230 --> 00:01:12.060
as I think all of you know.

00:01:12.060 --> 00:01:16.180
But anyway, this is for the
camera, so I always say that.

00:01:16.180 --> 00:01:20.440
The African, the Near East
and the Hebraic Section.

00:01:20.440 --> 00:01:26.070
We collect from 78
different countries in Africa,

00:01:26.070 --> 00:01:29.720
in the Middle East, in
Central Asia, in the Caucasus,

00:01:29.720 --> 00:01:35.250
and we collect materials primarily

00:01:35.250 --> 00:01:40.970
in this division, books,
and [inaudible].

00:01:40.970 --> 00:01:46.170
But we also have CDs, DVDs,
music, photographs, et cetera,

00:01:46.170 --> 00:01:50.100
which are in formats that
we don't usually collect,

00:01:50.100 --> 00:01:53.690
because there are other
divisions that have them.

00:01:53.690 --> 00:01:57.170
But we do have our own
series of materials,

00:01:57.170 --> 00:01:59.830
and of course, we have manuscripts.

00:01:59.830 --> 00:02:03.950
We have lithographs.

00:02:03.950 --> 00:02:06.350
And I'm mentioning
that in particular,

00:02:06.350 --> 00:02:11.520
because this would be part of the
discussion of today's presenter.

00:02:11.520 --> 00:02:18.790
These materials, we preserve, we
keep, we share, we serve, but also,

00:02:18.790 --> 00:02:21.290
we like to have discussed.

00:02:21.290 --> 00:02:22.980
We like to have --
to bring scholars.

00:02:22.980 --> 00:02:27.530
We like to have people who have
worked with these materials come

00:02:27.530 --> 00:02:32.590
to our reading room and talk
to us about these materials,

00:02:32.590 --> 00:02:34.870
about the way they were made,

00:02:34.870 --> 00:02:37.930
where they were made,
for whom they were made.

00:02:37.930 --> 00:02:41.230
It gives greater depth
to our collections,

00:02:41.230 --> 00:02:43.790
and it helps us understand
what we have.

00:02:43.790 --> 00:02:47.530
And it helps our patrons also
get a better understanding

00:02:47.530 --> 00:02:50.920
of how these materials can
be used, where they are,

00:02:50.920 --> 00:02:56.690
how accessible they are, sometimes
how rare they are as well.

00:02:56.690 --> 00:02:59.740
So we invite people
to make presentations.

00:02:59.740 --> 00:03:04.460
We do displays, and very often, we
have displays in our reading room.

00:03:04.460 --> 00:03:07.480
And we show icons that we collect.

00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:14.190
We've had major exhibitions,
both the Persian Book exhibit --

00:03:14.190 --> 00:03:16.570
we had the Hebraic book exhibit.

00:03:16.570 --> 00:03:21.010
We've had actually one on
Afghanistan, and these were letters

00:03:21.010 --> 00:03:27.400
that were written by
Afghans to Radio Free Europe

00:03:27.400 --> 00:03:32.500
that discussed various issues,
various personal problems

00:03:32.500 --> 00:03:38.410
that people -- young people,
older people face in Afghanistan.

00:03:38.410 --> 00:03:45.010
It's a unique collection of letters
that we have, in part, scanned,

00:03:45.010 --> 00:03:51.280
and that will eventually be
made available digitally online.

00:03:51.280 --> 00:03:54.310
But they've already been
organized, collated,

00:03:54.310 --> 00:03:58.760
but still not in a
fashion made available.

00:03:58.760 --> 00:04:03.600
Afghanistan has been a very
special focus of our collections,

00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:10.860
and we have acquired, from the
Afghan Media Research Center

00:04:10.860 --> 00:04:18.450
in Kabul, over 95,000 photographs.

00:04:18.450 --> 00:04:22.100
That's the largest
collection ever on Afghanistan,

00:04:22.100 --> 00:04:23.920
which have been digitized.

00:04:23.920 --> 00:04:27.400
Those photographs have
been digitized in Kabul

00:04:27.400 --> 00:04:31.370 position:56%
by the Afghan Media Research Center.

00:04:31.370 --> 00:04:36.790
They cover a period from
the late '70s to 2012.

00:04:36.790 --> 00:04:41.970
We've got films -- a collection of
films and videos from that center

00:04:41.970 --> 00:04:51.290
that are now in our research --
in our motion picture collection.

00:04:51.290 --> 00:04:53.850
And we have sound recordings
as well.

00:04:53.850 --> 00:04:56.950
That's in addition to the books,
the serials, the journals,

00:04:56.950 --> 00:04:59.630 position:56%
and the lithographs and manuscripts.

00:04:59.630 --> 00:05:03.140
I also want to recognize Hirad
Dinavari, who's been in charge

00:05:03.140 --> 00:05:08.400
of our Afghan collection, who's
done a fantastic job in organizing

00:05:08.400 --> 00:05:12.350
and having a lot of our
materials digitized and reviewed.

00:05:12.350 --> 00:05:16.180
And we have here Jan
Lancaster, who, herself,

00:05:16.180 --> 00:05:21.960
has gone through all our
manuscripts, Persian manuscripts

00:05:21.960 --> 00:05:24.560
and Afghan manuscripts
and lithographs,

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:27.890
and identified the
problems with them.

00:05:27.890 --> 00:05:32.350
We have the Preservation
Division here, that has looked

00:05:32.350 --> 00:05:37.430
at our materials and advised
us about what to do with them.

00:05:37.430 --> 00:05:43.330
So collecting is just the
beginning of the process

00:05:43.330 --> 00:05:49.500
by which we integrate the new
collections into our system,

00:05:49.500 --> 00:05:55.230
and sharing with us today is
Elham Bakhtary, who has worked

00:05:55.230 --> 00:05:58.310
with these materials, and who
will be sharing his research

00:05:58.310 --> 00:06:00.980
and his work on these materials.

00:06:00.980 --> 00:06:05.700
And to introduce him today
is our own Hirad Dinavari,

00:06:05.700 --> 00:06:10.040
our Persian specialist, who
has done tremendous work

00:06:10.040 --> 00:06:15.020
in developing the collections
and preserving them.

00:06:15.020 --> 00:06:16.530
So I'll pass it on to Hirad.

00:06:16.530 --> 00:06:18.590
Thank you.

