that are already starting to emerge
in the ideology of the Afghan state.

00:41:48.490 --> 00:41:50.930
And so you have one -- you have
Persian as sort of the language

00:41:50.930 --> 00:41:53.590
of culture, the language
of politics and diplomacy,

00:41:53.590 --> 00:41:54.890 position:56%
but on the other hand, you're trying

00:41:54.890 --> 00:41:57.500
to make Pashtu the
language of the military.

00:41:57.500 --> 00:42:03.330
And there are actually exams being
given in Pashtu as well, so --

00:42:03.330 --> 00:42:06.650
and a lot of the generals
and officers

00:42:06.650 --> 00:42:08.080
in the military were
actually Kizilbash

00:42:08.080 --> 00:42:10.490 position:56%
who were not really Pashtu speakers.

00:42:10.490 --> 00:42:13.510
And so you can kind
of imagine what kind

00:42:13.510 --> 00:42:15.560
of tensions these might
have created.

00:42:15.560 --> 00:42:18.540
Unfortunately, we don't
have any of these manuals,

00:42:18.540 --> 00:42:23.000
these military manuals
that are in Pashtu.

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:25.970
But under Emir Abdur Rahman Khan,

00:42:25.970 --> 00:42:28.630
similar manuals were produced,
and those are available.

00:42:28.630 --> 00:42:29.950
The British Library
has some of those,

00:42:29.950 --> 00:42:32.080
and I had a chance to
look at some of them.

00:42:32.080 --> 00:42:35.290
But otherwise, they're really
just straight translations

00:42:35.290 --> 00:42:37.960
of the British Indian manuals.

00:42:37.960 --> 00:42:40.220
And as far as --

00:42:40.220 --> 00:42:41.520
&gt;&gt; Sale, sale.

00:42:41.520 --> 00:42:44.180
&gt;&gt; Elham Bakhtary: The
sales of these materials,

00:42:44.180 --> 00:42:49.640
I would say that the polemics were
distributed throughout Afghanistan

00:42:49.640 --> 00:42:54.550
to provincial rulers, to be read
in public, either in the bazaars

00:42:54.550 --> 00:42:56.560
or in the masjids, in the mosques.

00:42:56.560 --> 00:42:59.400
As for "Shamsa Nihar," it
was available for purchase.

00:42:59.400 --> 00:43:05.440
Actually, info about how to
subscribe was in every issue.

00:43:05.440 --> 00:43:08.740
Based on what I understand
about subsequent newspapers

00:43:08.740 --> 00:43:12.970 position:56%
in Afghanistan, and other newspapers
in the region, such as Iran,

00:43:12.970 --> 00:43:16.590
usually these newspapers
would be forced upon people

00:43:16.590 --> 00:43:17.890
in the government.

00:43:17.890 --> 00:43:22.070
And they would be automatically
docked from their pay.

00:43:22.070 --> 00:43:26.190
So there was that, but also, in
"Shamsa Nihar," it does mention

00:43:26.190 --> 00:43:30.960
that you could -- anyone could
kind of go to a seller of hundis

00:43:30.960 --> 00:43:35.250
in Kabul, a [foreign language],
and they could purchase a hundi,

00:43:35.250 --> 00:43:38.300
and they would get a subscription

00:43:38.300 --> 00:43:41.240
of "Shamsa Nihar" every
week, or every month.

00:43:41.240 --> 00:43:44.700
Actually, it was never printed
regularly, but the idea was

00:43:44.700 --> 00:43:47.730
that it was going to be printed
every week, at least initially.

00:43:47.730 --> 00:43:49.880
And that they could sign
up, and they could get it.

00:43:49.880 --> 00:43:52.180
It's not clear if that shop

00:43:52.180 --> 00:43:55.450
that gave the hundis also
had individual issues.

00:43:55.450 --> 00:43:57.920
It does list the price
of an individual issue,

00:43:57.920 --> 00:44:00.420
but we don't really
have much indication

00:44:00.420 --> 00:44:02.850
as to whether this was
something that would be sold

00:44:02.850 --> 00:44:05.700
on the streets, like
a modern newspaper.

00:44:05.700 --> 00:44:07.310
There was also the possibility

00:44:07.310 --> 00:44:10.390
of purchasing the newspaper
from British India.

00:44:10.390 --> 00:44:13.070
So it gives you instructions
on how to purchase it if you're

00:44:13.070 --> 00:44:17.750
in Peshawar, but it's not really
clear how far it was distributed

00:44:17.750 --> 00:44:19.050
into India.

00:44:19.050 --> 00:44:23.220 position:56%
You could purchase it from Peshawar,
but we don't really have any info --

00:44:23.220 --> 00:44:25.700
idea of how far or
widely it was distributed.

00:44:25.700 --> 00:44:30.680
So we could -- we would limit
the readership to the area

00:44:30.680 --> 00:44:34.870
of Afghanistan and the
immediate area in British India.

00:44:34.870 --> 00:44:36.190
&gt;&gt; One other question, please.

00:44:36.190 --> 00:44:40.720
The Ulama had no printing way of
rebutting this, or participating

00:44:40.720 --> 00:44:44.140
in print in a debate with the Emir?

00:44:44.140 --> 00:44:45.440
&gt;&gt; Elham Bakhtary: Not yet.

00:44:45.440 --> 00:44:46.740
No, not yet.

00:44:46.740 --> 00:44:48.040
Not the ones in Afghanistan.

00:44:48.040 --> 00:44:50.120
The Tariqah had the
capability, and it's interesting

00:44:50.120 --> 00:44:53.470
that they don't respond
to these polemics,

00:44:53.470 --> 00:44:56.010
at least not that I know of.

00:44:56.010 --> 00:44:58.000
And I think that part
of the reason is

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:04.430
because he was the lone independent
Islamic ruler in the area.

00:45:04.430 --> 00:45:06.100
This would open up
another can of worms,

00:45:06.100 --> 00:45:10.220
if they tried to challenge
him openly about his ideas,

00:45:10.220 --> 00:45:14.520
because he really is the
authority on what is orthodoxy.

00:45:14.520 --> 00:45:19.790
But they do not challenge him,
and it's not until much later

00:45:19.790 --> 00:45:22.710
that you have private
presses in Afghanistan,

00:45:22.710 --> 00:45:25.220
well into the 20th century.

00:45:25.220 --> 00:45:28.690
&gt;&gt; Hiram Dinavari: One more
thing that came up in the work

00:45:28.690 --> 00:45:33.170
that you were doing is, it was
curious that a lot of classics

00:45:33.170 --> 00:45:37.730
of Persian literature,
[inaudible], et cetera, were --

00:45:37.730 --> 00:45:41.690
we tend to find most of
them are from India, really,

00:45:41.690 --> 00:45:44.550
and then partially
Iran and Central Asia.

00:45:44.550 --> 00:45:48.140
With the Afghan material, it
seemed that there was an attempt

00:45:48.140 --> 00:45:52.720
to make it unique -- the content
and subject uniquely Afghan.

00:45:52.720 --> 00:45:56.300
Could you say a few words, as
far as what your theory is,

00:45:56.300 --> 00:45:59.860
why these classics which were
obviously used in Afghanistan

00:45:59.860 --> 00:46:03.530
and not in Afghanistan were
not being produced [inaudible]?

00:46:03.530 --> 00:46:04.830
&gt;&gt; Elham Bakhtary: Right, yeah.

00:46:04.830 --> 00:46:06.740
So this is going to be a big
part of my dissertation research,

00:46:06.740 --> 00:46:10.020
and most of those ideas
are still in beta mode.

00:46:10.020 --> 00:46:12.440
But I will speak to
that a little bit.

00:46:12.440 --> 00:46:17.480
So in [inaudible] Iran, for
example, you do have reproductions

00:46:17.480 --> 00:46:22.220
of these epic works, of
poets like Hafez-e Shirazi,

00:46:22.220 --> 00:46:23.600
of "The Shahnameh" being produced.

00:46:23.600 --> 00:46:26.410
You don't have that in Afghanistan.

00:46:26.410 --> 00:46:32.020
And my theory is that
the Emir Sher Ali Khan,

00:46:32.020 --> 00:46:37.320
when he talks about the history of
Afghanistan, he characterizes it

00:46:37.320 --> 00:46:41.000
as a terra nullius of savagery,

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:43.870
that Afghanistan was
basically an unknown land

00:46:43.870 --> 00:46:46.670
until he had come to power.

00:46:46.670 --> 00:46:47.970
Afghans were ignorant.

00:46:47.970 --> 00:46:52.690
Afghans lived in darkness, and
I believe that he did not want

00:46:52.690 --> 00:46:56.660
to print these great works
because it would remind people

00:46:56.660 --> 00:46:58.070
of Horsani [assumed
spelling] civilization.

00:46:58.070 --> 00:47:02.180 position:56%
It would remind people of a time
that, indeed, there was civilization

00:47:02.180 --> 00:47:04.090
in Afghanistan, and it
was certainly better

00:47:04.090 --> 00:47:06.950 position:56%
than anything the Emir was building.

00:47:06.950 --> 00:47:11.450
The Emir wanted to portray the
past as simply one of darkness,

00:47:11.450 --> 00:47:14.040
because it would sharpen the
contrast of his own rule.

00:47:14.040 --> 00:47:16.300
And I believe that, unlike
the Punjabs were trying

00:47:16.300 --> 00:47:21.630
to associate their rule with
earlier Iranian dynasties

00:47:21.630 --> 00:47:25.260
like the Saffarids, Emir Sher Ali
Khan did not want any association

00:47:25.260 --> 00:47:30.000
with any previous rulers,
both in Afghanistan and Islam.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:32.670
Like the Tariqah, he
actually really tries

00:47:32.670 --> 00:47:35.710
to associate his rule most
closely with the Salaf,

00:47:35.710 --> 00:47:38.880
with the Prophet Mohammad
and the Rashidun Caliphate.

00:47:38.880 --> 00:47:42.420
That's really the history that
he tries to attach his rule,

00:47:42.420 --> 00:47:44.680
and that's how -- and that's
one of the connections I'm going

00:47:44.680 --> 00:47:50.340
to be trying to draw between the
Tariqah and Emir Sher Ali Khan.

00:47:50.340 --> 00:47:51.640
Sure.

00:47:51.640 --> 00:47:53.310
&gt;&gt; Do we have a full list of
the publications that came

00:47:53.310 --> 00:47:56.830
out of Sher Ali Khan's press?

00:47:56.830 --> 00:48:02.710
&gt;&gt; Elham Bakhtary: So there's a lot
of speculation about certain works

00:48:02.710 --> 00:48:05.160
that were produced, but
have been destroyed.

00:48:05.160 --> 00:48:09.770
So there are lists -- I have
a list of works that do exist.

00:48:09.770 --> 00:48:16.760 position:56%
Robert McChesney at NYU has compiled
a list of works that were produced

00:48:16.760 --> 00:48:19.140 position:56%
from the time of Emir Sher Ali Khan.

00:48:19.140 --> 00:48:22.640
But there are also other works that
we don't have any extant copies

00:48:22.640 --> 00:48:25.040
of them, but people speculate --

00:48:25.040 --> 00:48:29.870 position:56%
especially Afghan scholars speculate
them to have been produced.

00:48:29.870 --> 00:48:34.150
And I have some information on that
material, if you're interested,

00:48:34.150 --> 00:48:35.450
and I could share it with you.

00:48:35.450 --> 00:48:37.190
[ Inaudible ]

00:48:37.190 --> 00:48:43.150 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: With respect to
using [inaudible] as the [inaudible]

00:48:43.150 --> 00:48:51.610
for propaganda, was he also
pushing for reform, organization,

00:48:51.610 --> 00:48:58.650
changes in the society, and
if so, what were the changes

00:48:58.650 --> 00:49:02.280
that he was trying to
[inaudible] from the richest issue?

00:49:02.280 --> 00:49:09.420
What social, economic, cultural
changes was he pushing for?

00:49:09.420 --> 00:49:11.760
&gt;&gt; Elham Bakhtary: Emir
Sher Ali Khan is trying

00:49:11.760 --> 00:49:16.850
to really just create a central
authority in Afghanistan.

00:49:16.850 --> 00:49:22.780
So the Afghan kingdom was really
founded on a series of partnerships

00:49:22.780 --> 00:49:27.610
with other chieftains
in the Durrani tribe.

00:49:27.610 --> 00:49:31.660
And so there was real no -- there
was not really any central kind

00:49:31.660 --> 00:49:33.180
of leadership throughout
the country.

00:49:33.180 --> 00:49:38.210
There was much autonomy divided
between the different tribes,

00:49:38.210 --> 00:49:44.180 position:56%
and also between the different
brothers, even, in the royal family.

00:49:44.180 --> 00:49:46.990
And he's trying to centralize the
entire country, and he's trying

00:49:46.990 --> 00:49:49.840
to do this primarily
through an army.

00:49:49.840 --> 00:49:52.130
And in "Shamsa Nihar,"
he tries to dress this

00:49:52.130 --> 00:49:56.030
up as creating civilization,
as educating people.

00:49:56.030 --> 00:49:58.880
But when you really look
at it, the civilization

00:49:58.880 --> 00:50:01.980
that he's talking about, the
education that he's talking about,

00:50:01.980 --> 00:50:09.040
the production in arts and crafts,
it all has to do with the military.

00:50:09.040 --> 00:50:13.340
When he talks about education,
for example, and creating scholars

00:50:13.340 --> 00:50:16.370
out of Afghans, he's just
talking about sending them

00:50:16.370 --> 00:50:18.750
to these military schools
that he's established,

00:50:18.750 --> 00:50:21.580
and having them learn
military formations,

00:50:21.580 --> 00:50:23.660
and drills along the
British-Indian model.

00:50:23.660 --> 00:50:27.360 position:56%
When he talks about arts and crafts,
right, bringing manufacturing,

00:50:27.360 --> 00:50:28.860
he's just talking about
the factories

00:50:28.860 --> 00:50:31.030
that he's established
to produce weapons.

00:50:31.030 --> 00:50:34.270
Okay? So even though he's trying
to dress it up as civilization,

00:50:34.270 --> 00:50:38.110
what he's really just talking about
is this militaries that he's trying

00:50:38.110 --> 00:50:40.430
to create, to consolidate
his authority

00:50:40.430 --> 00:50:43.420
over the entirety of Afghanistan.

